userStories.notes:
File: platform/plugin-tools/src/commands/build.ts

Bug: Lines 790-819. When a plugin defines onNavigate, the IIFE wrapper monkey-patches history.pushState and history.replaceState:
```
var origPushState = history.pushState.bind(history);
var origReplaceState = history.replaceState.bind(history);
history.pushState = function(...args) { origPushState(...args); onNav(); };
history.replaceState = function(...args) { origReplaceState(...args); onNav(); };
```

The teardown (lines 806-819) unconditionally restores the originals:
```
history.pushState = origPushState;
history.replaceState = origReplaceState;
```

If two plugins (A then B) both define onNavigate, the chain is:
- A patches: origPushState_A = original, history.pushState = A's wrapper
- B patches: origPushState_B = A's wrapper, history.pushState = B's wrapper

If A tears down first: history.pushState = origPushState_A (original). This removes B's wrapper entirely — B stops receiving navigation events.

Fix: Only restore if the current function is still OUR wrapper. The teardown should check:
```
if (history.pushState === ourPushStateWrapper) {
  history.pushState = origPushState;
}
if (history.replaceState === ourReplaceStateWrapper) {
  history.replaceState = origReplaceState;
}
```

This means the wrapper functions need to be stored in named variables that are accessible in the teardown scope. Adjust the IIFE template accordingly.

This is the same safe pattern used by browser extensions and userscripts that monkey-patch shared globals.
